Think through the deep problem of measuring code quality in test code versus production code, and whether the same rules and thresholds should apply to both. Tests have fundamentally different structural properties than production code: they are typically longer functions, they have more repetition (by design, to be readable in isolation), they use assertion-heavy code that has many branches, and they may use patterns like fixture factories or data providers that look like code smells but are standard testing practice.

Reason through each of the following questions. First, should cyclomatic and cognitive complexity thresholds be higher or lower for test functions than for production functions? A parametrized test with many assertions might have high cyclomatic complexity but be completely appropriate and readable. Conversely, a test that has complex setup logic might indicate that the production code being tested is too hard to instantiate, which is itself a quality signal. Second, should code duplication detection be more lenient in test code? Copy-pasted test cases are often intentional to preserve test isolation and readability. What is the right minimum clone size for test code, and how should a clone detector identify whether it is analyzing test files? Third, should documentation requirements differ for test code? Test function names are often self-documenting (test_should_return_error_when_input_is_negative) and docstrings add little value. But fixture functions, test helpers, and shared setup methods may need documentation. How should a documentation coverage metric handle this distinction? Fourth, what quality metrics are specifically useful for test code that do not apply to production code: test-to-production code ratio, assertion density per test function, test coupling (tests that share mutable state), and test hermetics (tests that depend on external services). Design a separate test quality profile for the Heimdall Quality tool with distinct thresholds and rules for each of these dimensions.
